          <option name="text" value="You are incredibly close! You successfully resolved 47 out of the 48 linting issues, and your `firebase.json` target path is correct.&#10;&#10;However, two distinct roadblocks are still stopping the deployment: **1 final line-length lint error** and the persistent Windows **`ENOENT` shell spawning error**.&#10;&#10;Here is how to smash both of them completely.&#10;&#10;---&#10;&#10;## Step 1: Squash the Absolute Last Lint Error&#10;&#10;Open the file `functions/src/genkit-sample.ts` in your editor. Go to **line 8**.&#10;&#10;It is exactly 81 characters long (1 character over the limit!). Just drop a piece of that line down to a new line using `Enter`, or delete a single unnecessary character/space to pull it under 80 characters.&#10;&#10;---&#10;&#10;## Step 2: Fix the Windows `ENOENT` Spawning Bug&#10;&#10;Even when you fix that lint error, the deployment will still crash with `ENOENT`. This is because Node's `child_process.spawn` on Windows struggles to execute the raw `npm` command directly without a shell interpreter context.&#10;&#10;To fix this for good on Windows, change the `predeploy` command structure in your `firebase.json` file to explicitly use the shell wrapper (`cmd.exe /c`).&#10;&#10;1. Open `firebase.json` in your root directory.&#10;2. Update the `functions` configuration to format the commands like this:&#10;&#10;```json&#10;&quot;functions&quot;: [&#10;  {&#10;    &quot;codebase&quot;: &quot;default&quot;,&#10;    &quot;source&quot;: &quot;functions&quot;,&#10;    &quot;predeploy&quot;: [&#10;      &quot;cmd.exe /c \&quot;npm --prefix functions run lint\&quot;&quot;,&#10;      &quot;cmd.exe /c \&quot;npm --prefix functions run build\&quot;&quot;&#10;    ]&#10;  }&#10;]&#10;&#10;```&#10;&#10;*(Apply the exact same `cmd.exe /c &quot;...&quot;` wrapping style to your other codebases like `cb001`, `cb7001`, etc., if they are listed inside your `firebase.json`).*&#10;&#10;---&#10;&#10;## Step 3: Run the Best-Practice Deploy Command&#10;&#10;Once those two adjustments are saved, completely bypass the global CLI layer by using `npx` targeted specifically at your primary functions codebase.&#10;&#10;Run this from your root folder:&#10;&#10;```powershell&#10;npx firebase deploy --only functions:default&#10;&#10;```&#10;&#10;This ensures Firebase only touches the specific codebase we just finished validating and organizing. How does the terminal respond to the wrapped command structure?&#10;&#10;File: genkit-sample.ts&#10;```ts&#10;// Gemini Developer API models and Vertex Express Mode models depend on API keys.&#10;```" />
